textBeforeTable: See also[edit] Eu vi ele. = "I saw him/it." Eu o vi. → In the colloquial speech of some parts of Brazil, it is being abandoned in favor of the nominative form ele. Detêm-no como prisioneiro. = "They detain him/it as a prisoner." Becomes -no after a nasal sound: Ei-lo! = "Behold him/it!" eis: After Deu-no-lo relutantemente. = "He gave him/it to us reluctantly." nos: After Fi-lo ficar contente. = "I made him/it become happy." fiz: After Quero pô-lo ali. = "I want to put him/it there." pôs: After Posso vê-lo? = "May I see him/it?" ver: After Becomes -lo after verb forms ending in -r, -s, or -z, the pronouns nos and vos, and the adverb eis; the ending letter causing the change disappears.
